name: 5,8,11,14-eicosatetraenoic acid
Reason: The compound 5,8,11,14-eicosatetraenoic acid is a long-chain fatty acid with four double bonds and a carboxylic acid group. The basic hydrocarbon chain similar to eicosane would have a melting point around 36.4 degrees Celsius (for eicosane). Each double bond in a fatty acid typically lowers the melting point by approximately -12 degrees Celsius due to decreased van der Waals interactions as they cause kinks in the chain which inhibits tight packing. The carboxylic acid group will increase the melting point due to the ability to form hydrogen bonds; however, because there's only one carboxylic acid group and it's at the end of a long chain, its effect will be mitigated by the overall structure. The hydrogen bonding effect is estimated to add approximately +15 degrees Celsius to the melting point. Combining the effects of the double bonds and the carboxylic acid group: 36.4 - (4 * 12) + 15 = 36.4 - 48 + 15 = 3.4 degrees Celsius.
